"Biographies of Zhang Shizhi and Feng Tang"

Zhang Shizhi, the Minister of Justice, was from Duyaang. His courtesy name was Ji. He lived together with his elder brother, Zhong. He served as a Cavalry Gentleman due to his family's wealth, serving Emperor Xiaowen. For ten years, he received no promotion and was unknown. Shizhi said, "Serving in office for so long has depleted Zhong's property, and I have not succeeded." He wished to resign and return home. The Gentleman-at-arms Yuan Ang knew of his worth and regretted his departure, so he requested that Shizhi be transferred to fill the post of Yezhe (Court Attendant). After Shizhi had completed his audience, he spoke on matters of expediency as he had previously mentioned. Emperor Wen said, "Keep it low; do not engage in overly high theories, but say what can be implemented now." Thus, Shizhi spoke for a long time about the events between the Qin and Han dynasties, explaining why Qin lost and Han rose. Emperor Wen praised him as good, and appointed Shizhi as Chief Yezhe.

Shizhi accompanied the Emperor on a tour and ascended the Tiger Enclosure. The Emperor asked the Superintendent of Shanglin about the registers of various birds and beasts. After more than ten questions, the Superintendent looked left and right and could answer none. The Clerk of the Tiger Enclosure, standing by, answered the Emperor’s questions about the registers of birds and beasts in great detail, wishing to show his ability to respond orally with endless quickness. Emperor Wen said, "Should officials not be like this? The Superintendent is useless!" He then ordered Shizhi to appoint the Clerk as Superintendent of Shanglin. Shizhi stepped forward and said, "Your Majesty, what kind of person do you consider Marquis Jiang, Zhou Bo, to be?" The Emperor said, "A worthy elder." Shizhi asked again, "What kind of person do you consider Marquis Dongyang, Zhang Xianghe, to be?" The Emperor again said, "A worthy elder." Shizhi said, "Marquis Jiang and Marquis Dongyang are called worthy elders, yet these two men could hardly speak when discussing matters. How could they imitate this Clerk, who is chattering with a sharp and quick tongue? Moreover, Qin relied on clerks skilled with pen and brush. These clerks competed with each other in speed and harsh scrutiny, but their flaw was that they only attended to formalities, lacking genuine compassion. Therefore, their faults were not heard of, and the dynasty declined gradually until the Second Emperor, when the empire collapsed like earth crumbling. Now, Your Majesty, because the Clerk is eloquent, you promote him beyond his rank. I fear the world will follow this trend, competing in eloquence without substance. Furthermore, the lower ranks imitate the upper ranks faster than shadows follow objects or echoes follow sounds. Actions and decisions must be carefully considered." Emperor Wen said, "Good." He then stopped and did not appoint the Clerk.

The Emperor entered his carriage, summoned Shizhi to ride with him, and drove slowly, asking Shizhi about the flaws of Qin. Shizhi answered with straightforward truth. Upon reaching the palace, the Emperor appointed Shizhi as Commander of the Gongche (Public Carriages).

After some time, he became Gentleman-at-arms. Accompanying the Emperor to Baling, he sat facing north near the latrine. At that time, Lady Shen accompanied the Emperor. The Emperor pointed out the road to Xinfeng to Lady Shen, saying, "This is the road to Handan." He had Lady Shen play the se, and the Emperor himself leaned on the se and sang, his mood sad and mournful. He looked at his ministers and said, "Alas! If we use stone from Beishan for the outer coffin, fill the gaps with hemp and cotton, and seal them with lacquer, how could it be moved?" Those around him all said, "Good." Shizhi stepped forward and said, "If there is anything desirable inside, even if sealed with the stone of Nanshan, there would still be cracks; if there is nothing desirable inside, even without a stone coffin, what sorrow is there?" Emperor Wen praised him as good. Later, Shizhi was appointed Minister of Justice.

After some time, the Emperor went out through the Zhongwei Bridge. A man came out from under the bridge, and the imperial horses were startled. The Emperor ordered cavalry to capture him and handed him over to the Minister of Justice. Shizhi investigated and questioned him. The man said, "I am a county resident. I heard the clearance order and hid under the bridge. After a long time, I thought the procession had passed, so I came out. Seeing the imperial carriages and cavalry, I ran away." The Minister of Justice sentenced him: one person violating the clearance order should be fined. Emperor Wen was angry and said, "This man personally startled my horse. My horse happened to be gentle; if it had been another horse, would it not have injured me? Yet the Minister of Justice only sentences him to a fine!" Shizhi said, "The law is what the Son of Heaven shares with the world. Now, if the law is thus and we make the punishment heavier, the law will not be trusted by the people. Moreover, at that moment, if Your Majesty had ordered immediate execution, it would have been over. Now that it has been handed to the Minister of Justice, the Minister of Justice is the balance of the world. If he tilts once, the application of law throughout the world will become arbitrary. Where will the people place their hands and feet? I beg Your Majesty to consider this." After a long time, the Emperor said, "The Minister of Justice’s judgment is correct."

Later, someone stole a jade ring from before the seat in the High Ancestral Temple. He was captured, and Emperor Wen, angry, handed him to the Minister of Justice for trial. Shizhi investigated according to the law: stealing items used by the ancestral temple warrants execution by decapitation in the market. He submitted this sentence. The Emperor was furious and said, "This man is lawless, stealing vessels from the temple of the late Emperor. I handed him to the Minister of Justice intending to execute his clan, but you submit a sentence according to the law. This is not how I wish to serve and inherit the ancestral temple." Shizhi removed his cap, kowtowed, and apologized, saying, "The law is sufficient as it is. Moreover, crimes are equal, but distinguished by rebellion or obedience. Now, if we execute the clan for stealing temple vessels, what if, by a chance in ten thousand, a foolish person takes a handful of earth from Changling? How would Your Majesty increase the punishment?" After a long time, Emperor Wen discussed it with the Empress Dowager, and then allowed the Minister of Justice’s sentence. At that time, the Commander-in-Chief, Marquis Tiao, Zhou Yafu, and the Chancellor of Liang, Marquis Shandu, Wang Tiankai, saw that Shizhi held his opinions fairly, so they became close friends with him. From then on, Zhang the Minister of Justice was praised throughout the world.

Later, Emperor Wen died, and Emperor Jing ascended the throne. Shizhi was afraid and claimed illness. He wished to resign, fearing great punishment; he wished to appear and apologize, but did not know how it would go. Following Wang Sheng’s plan, he finally appeared and apologized, and Emperor Jing did not punish him.

Wang Sheng was a recluse skilled in the teachings of Huang-Lao. Once summoned to sit in the court, when the Three Excellencies and Nine Ministers were all standing, Wang Sheng, an old man, said, "My sock has come undone," and looked at Zhang the Minister of Justice, saying, "Tie my sock for me!" Shizhi knelt and tied it. Afterward, someone said to Wang Sheng, "Why did you humiliate Zhang the Minister of Justice in court, making him kneel to tie your sock?" Wang Sheng said, "I am old and lowly, and I judge that I am ultimately of no benefit to Zhang the Minister of Justice. Zhang the Minister of Justice is currently a famous minister in the world. I intentionally humiliated the Minister of Justice, making him kneel to tie my sock, to enhance his reputation." When the nobles heard this, they esteemed Wang Sheng and respected Zhang the Minister of Justice.

Zhang the Minister of Justice served Emperor Jing for over a year, then became Chancellor of the Prince of Huainan, still due to previous faults. After a long time, Shizhi died. His son was Zhang Zhi, courtesy name Changgong, who served as a Grand Master, then was dismissed. Because he could not accommodate himself to the contemporary world, he never served in office for the rest of his life.

Feng Tang’s grandfather was from Zhao. His father moved to Dai. When Han rose, they moved to Anling. Tang was known for filial piety and served as Chief of the Gentleman-at-arms registry, serving Emperor Wen. When the Emperor passed by in his carriage, he asked Tang, "Old man, why are you a Gentleman? Where is your home?" Tang answered truthfully. Emperor Wen said, "When I lived in Dai, my Food Supervisor Gao Qu often spoke to me of the worthiness of the Zhao general Li Qi, who fought at Julu. Now, every time I eat, my thoughts are not absent from Julu. Do you, old man, know him?" Tang replied, "He is not as good as Lian Po and Li Mu as generals." The Emperor said, "Why?" Tang said, "When my grandfather was in Zhao, he was an officer commanding troops and was friendly with Li Mu. My father was formerly Chancellor of Dai and was friendly with the Zhao general Li Qi, knowing his character." The Emperor, having heard of the characters of Lian Po and Li Mu, was very pleased and beat his thighs, saying, "Alas! If only I could have Lian Po and Li Mu as my generals now, would I worry about the Xiongnu?" Tang said, "Your servant! Even if Your Majesty obtained Lian Po and Li Mu, you could not use them." The Emperor was angry, rose, and entered the inner palace. After a long time, he summoned Tang and reproached him, saying, "Why did you humiliate me in public? Could you not find a private place?" Tang apologized, saying, "I am a rustic person and do not know taboos."

At that time, the Xiongnu had recently invaded Chaona in great force, killing the Commandant of Beidi, Ang. The Emperor was concerned about the Hu raiders, so he finally asked Tang again, "How do you know I cannot use Lian Po and Li Mu?" Tang replied, "I have heard that when ancient kings dispatched generals, they knelt and pushed the carriage wheel, saying, 'Within the threshold, I decide; outside the threshold, the general decides.' Military merits and rewards were all decided outside, and reported upon return. This is not empty talk. My grandfather said that when Li Mu was a Zhao general stationed at the border, the rents from the military markets were all used by him to entertain the soldiers. Rewards were decided outside, without interference from the center. He was entrusted with responsibility and required to achieve success, so Li Mu was able to fully exert his wisdom and ability. He dispatched one thousand three hundred chariots, thirteen thousand mounted archers, and one hundred thousand elite soldiers. Thus, he drove the Chanyu north, defeated the Donghu, destroyed Danlin, suppressed the strong Qin in the west, and supported Han and Wei in the south. At that time, Zhao nearly achieved hegemony. Later, when King Qian of Zhao ascended the throne, his mother was a singer. After King Qian ascended, he listened to the slander of Guo Kai, finally executed Li Mu, and ordered Yan Ju to replace him. Thus, the army was defeated, the soldiers fled, and Zhao was captured and destroyed by Qin. Now, I secretly hear that Wei Shang is the Governor of Yunzhong. He uses all the rents from the military markets to entertain the soldiers, and from his private funds, every five days he slaughters an ox to entertain guests, military officers, and attendants. Thus, the Xiongnu avoid him from afar and do not approach the Yunzhong passes. When the enemy once entered, Shang led chariots and cavalry to attack them, killing many of them. The soldiers are all sons of families, recruited from the fields to serve in the army. How would they know the small registers and tally slips? They fight hard all day, beheading and capturing enemies, and submit their merits to the headquarters. If one word does not correspond, clerical officials bind them with the law. Their rewards are not carried out, while the officials strictly apply the law. I am foolish, but I think Your Majesty’s laws are too clear, rewards too light, and punishments too heavy. Moreover, the Governor of Yunzhong, Wei Shang, was accused of a discrepancy of six levels in reporting beheaded heads and captured enemies. Your Majesty handed him to the officials, stripped him of his rank, and sentenced him to penal labor. From this, it can be said that even if Your Majesty obtained Lian Po and Li Mu, you could not use them. I am truly foolish and have touched upon taboos. I deserve death, I deserve death!" Emperor Wen was pleased. That day, he ordered Feng Tang to hold a tally and pardon Wei Shang, restoring him as Governor of Yunzhong, and appointed Tang as Commander of Chariots and Cavalry, in charge of the chariot and infantry soldiers of the Commander-in-Chief and the commanderies and kingdoms.

In the seventh year, Emperor Jing ascended the throne and appointed Tang as Chancellor of Chu, but he was dismissed. When Emperor Wu ascended, he sought worthy and good men, and Feng Tang was recommended. Tang was then over ninety years old and could no longer serve in office, so Tang’s son, Feng Sui, was appointed as a Gentleman. Sui’s courtesy name was Wangsun. He was also an extraordinary man and was friendly with me.

The Grand Historian says: Zhang Ji’s words regarding worthy elders show that he upheld the law and did not flatter opinions; Feng Gong’s discussion of generals is meaningful! Meaningful! The saying goes, "If you do not know a person, look at his friends." What the two gentlemen praised can be inscribed in the ancestral temple. The Book of Documents says, "Not partial, not partisan, the Way of the King is broad; not partisan, not partial, the Way of the King is smooth." Zhang Ji and Feng Gong are close to this. [end of text]


